				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hot on the heels of the <a href="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/20/what-millennials-want-is-cookies-shaped-like-pizza/">pizza cookie</a> comes a new pizza-related innovation: Push for Pizza, an app that lets you order a pizza by pressing a button.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an introductory <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hw07EXR8mJg">video</a>, Cyrus Summerlin, who foundedÂ Push for Pizza withÂ Max Hellerstein), says the app will be âlike Uber for pizzaâ (Mr. Hellerstein then admonishes him, in a strange metatextual moment, that âwe canât say Uberâ). But as many have pointed out, Push for Pizza is actually more like <a href="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/whither-yo/?_php=true&amp;_type=blogs&amp;_r=0">Yo</a>, the much-heralded app you can use to say âYoâ to people. At Slate, Jeffrey Bloomer <a href="//www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2014/08/05/how_does_push_for_pizza_work_reviewing_the_free_new_pizza_delivery_service.html">explains</a>:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe app updates food delivery for theÂ <a href="//www.slate.com/blogs/business_insider/2014/06/19/marc_andreessen_explains_why_mobile_app_yo_is_a_big_deal_one_bit_signaling.html">Yo era</a>: After entering onetime information about your location and payment method, it calls up the nearest participating pizza place and offers you either a cheese or pepperoni pie in just three taps, from start to finish.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Or, as Valleywagâs Sam Biddle <a href="//valleywag.gawker.com/meet-a-teenage-pizza-startup-entrepreneur-the-future-o-1616455994">puts it</a>: âSince when did Yo stop being idiotic and start being mimicked?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hellerstein tells him in a GChat interview that heâs a fan of Yo: âYo is super cool.â He adds that Push for Pizza and Yo will be âworking together on some promotion,â and that âwe offer two completely different products, and if anything, work hand in hand.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Despite the fact that it really does say onlyÂ âYo,â unless you <a href="//www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/yo-app-hacked-to-say-things-that-arent-yo-9551769.html">hack it</a>, Yo has been <a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/blogs/breakout/yo--critics-are-missing-the-point-125459504.html">praised</a> for its versatility. And its creator, Or Arbel, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/18/with-single-word-yo-messaging-app-gets-people-talking/">told</a> William Alden and Sydney Ember of The Times, âPeople think itâs just an app that says âYo.â But itâs really not. We like to call it context-based messaging. You understand by the context what is being said.â He added that publications could use the app to send âYosâ to subscribers, and that one of his investors used it instead of texting his wife, âI love you.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All of this raises the question of whether Push for Pizza can break the seeming restrictions of its form and offer context-based pizza. Will people start sending love pizzas? Sorry pizzas? Hate pizzas (unwanted <a href="//kotaku.com/cops-show-up-live-on-warcraft-stream-after-troll-phones-1476642136">pizza delivery</a> is already a relatively common harassment strategy among online trolls)? Will companies push you free pizzas to thank you for your business, or to entice you? Or (probably more likely) will Push for Pizzaâs next move just be offering a simple means to order all foods? Mr. Summerlin <a href="//techcrunch.com/2014/08/05/push-for-pizza-is-yo-for-food-delivery/">tells</a> TechCrunchâs Kyle Russell: âWe always talk about an umbrella food button ordering system. Cookies, tacos, burgers, everything, you name it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some have questioned whether Yo-style apps are really the wave of the future â and, if they are, whether thatâs a good thing. At The Wall Street Journal, Christopher Mims <a href="//online.wsj.com/articles/is-silicon-valley-investing-in-the-wrong-stuff-1404688048">looks at</a> âsocial networks that allow you to send only the message âYoâ to your contactsâ and âfood-delivery services valued at $400 millionâ and argues that âthe entire Bay Area appears to have given up on solving anything but its own problems: those afflicting the same 20-somethings who are building these startups.â He writes:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs hard not to look at round after round of funding for companies with negative cash flow, companies that are solving problems that afflict just a tiny portion of the planetâs population, and think that the problem is really about misplaced investor enthusiasm: that is, the bubble that the tech industry may or may not be in right now.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, he concludes, whether weâre actually in a bubble matters less than âwhether, from the perspective of net social benefits, or even just long-term return on capital, the problem of replacing instant messaging is a better investment than countless other potential businesses in the $16 trillion real economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Push for Pizza certainly solves a first-world problem, and a very specific one at that. As Ellis Hamburger of The Verge <a href="//www.theverge.com/2014/8/5/5970801/push-for-pizza-app-might-change-your-life">puts it</a>:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs 3:00 AM. Youâre hungry. Your buds are hungry. The Cool Ranch Doritos bag is long past empty. âOh my God, thereâs an app for this,â says your bro Scott.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The fact that you and your buds might also be stoned â and, as BetaBeatâs Sage Lazzaro <a href="//betabeat.com/2014/08/new-app-lets-you-order-pizza-with-the-push-of-one-button-makes-life-worth-living/">suggests</a>, that the Push for Pizza team might have been stoned at the time of its inception â is something the founders allude to in their video (watch for the smoke) but wonât directly address. They are, however, not even 20-somethings but teenagers (Mr. Hellerstein is 19), and their ambitions feel correspondingly teenage. Their video has none of the making-the-world-a-better-place self-seriousnessÂ <a href="//www.npr.org/2014/04/17/304150243/silicon-valley-asks-is-your-startup-really-making-the-world-better">satirized on HBOâs âSilicon Valleyâ</a> â all theyâre promising is fast, easy food. Mr. Hellerstein tells Mr. Biddle he would like to own a âpizza jetâ (somewhat disappointingly, a jet with a Push for Pizza logo, rather than a jet made out of pizza). And his response to Mr. Biddleâs final questions may be a fitting summation of the Push for Pizza ethos:</p>
<p data-textannotation-id="b0fa973ed7153fc72758318fef1085ef">âWe are super excited about it, had no idea it would get this big</p>
<p data-textannotation-id="d985a8cdc349f39a26d82c6923669301">âthis quick</p>
<p data-textannotation-id="11d943fbc166df9f62b0e1536f43adaa">âreally excited to turn the world upside down</p>
<p data-textannotation-id="e1ad0a5125d378816473eaab86236a5c">âand breadsticks, coming soonâ</p>
<p data-textannotation-id="e1ad0a5125d378816473eaab86236a5c">Sure, thereâs a whiff of âSilicon Valley,â though itâs not totally clear whether heâs kidding about turning the world upside down. And thereâs also a reminder that Push for Pizza is, despite the hype, just pizza. Not even breadsticks â yet.</p>
	</div>
